article.description:
Shawn Marion scored 18 of his 27 points in the
third period, and the Phoenix Suns beat Sacramento 109-84 Thursday
night, ending the Kings' four-game winning streak.
article.headline: Phoenix snaps Kings' four-game win streak
article.linkText: Suns send Kings to worst loss of the season
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Shawn Marion returned to his All-Star self, and the Phoenix Suns rode his hot shooting to a 109-84 victory over the Sacramento Kings on Thursday night.
 
Marion
"We got the old Shawn back," Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said. Marion scored 18 of his 27 points in the third period as the Suns ended the Kings' four-game winning streak and handed them their worst defeat of the season. Sacramento's previous worst loss was 108-84 to New Orleans on Feb. 5. Stephon Marbury added 26 points for Phoenix, which moved a half-game game ahead of idle Houston in the race for the eighth and final playoff spot in the Western Conference. The teams play in Houston on Sunday. The loss reduced the Kings' Pacific Division lead to 2½ games over idle Portland and left them 3½ games behind Dallas for the best record in the West. Marion, who had been in a recent slump, scored 13 of the Suns' first 15 points in the third period, capping that outburst with consecutive 3-pointers that gave Phoenix a 64-47 lead with 7:05 remaining. He later scored on a length-of-the-court drive and added another 3-pointer. "This was the Shawn we're used to seeing," Johnson said. "He was very efficient, making passes, getting defensive steals. I also liked his rebounding and shot selection." Marbury also enjoyed Marion's overall play. "Shawn stepped up his game big-time in the second half," Marbury said. "We need that out of him. He played phenomenally." Marion, who shot 11-for-18 from the field, praised the team's performance rather than his own. "Everybody was involved," he said. "We were just doing what we wanted to do. We were shutting them down, getting stops, rebounding and pushing the ball." The Kings' Chris Webber just missed his 16th career triple double and second against the Suns this season. He finished with 22 points, 11 rebounds and nine assists. Mike Bibby scored 20 points, and Keon Clark had 13 for Sacramento. Joe Johnson had 15 points for the Suns and Jake Voskuhl added 13. Marion and Amare Stoudemire had 11 rebounds apiece for the Suns and Bo Outlaw had 10 as Phoenix outrebounded the Kings 51-40. Webber and coach Rick Adelman questioned the Kings' determination. "I think you have to look in the mirror," Webber said. "I question our effort tonight. ... If we want a championship, we're going to have to stop being so damn cool." Adelman agreed. "We played awful," he said. "We didn't have any energy or urgency to play. I'm disappointed with the way we played. "Maybe because we've been playing at home and winning, we think it's going to be easy." With a 19-4 run, including spurts of 9-0 and 8-0 during the middle of the second period, the Suns built a 45-29 lead with 2:41 remaining before halftime. But the Kings, limited to just four free throws for 5:26, reeled off four consecutive baskets in just over a minute and reduced the lead by halftime to 49-42. Marbury, managing to knife through Sacramento's packed-in-the-middle defense, scored 18 points in the first half. Peja Stojakovic, averaging 19 points, misfired on all five of his shots in the first half when the Kings -- second in the league in field goal percentage -- shot a dismal 37 percent (17-for-46). He finished 1-for-7 and had four points. Stoudemire, Phoenix's rookie sensation, also failed to make a basket in the half. But he hit 5-of-6 free throws and grabbed eight rebounds. He wound up with eight points. Game notes
Muhammad Ali and baseball Hall of Famer Dave Winfield. ... Tom Gugliotta, normally a forward, made a rare start at center for Phoenix. ... Center Jake Tsakalidis returned to the Suns after missing 34 games because of surgery on his lower back, but did not play. ... The Kings had only 10 available players because neither starting center Vlade Divac (bronchitis) nor reserve forward Lawrence Funderburke (personal reasons) made the trip. Divac's absence -- it is not known how many games he will miss -- figures to hurt the Kings. "I think Vlade is the key to their team," Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said. ... The Suns placed guard Randy Brown on the injured list with a strained left calf.
